  "title": "Unit 7 applied, geometric, and computational interpretation",
  "body": " Unit 7 applied, geometric, and computational interpretation  These are solution sketches for the additional applied and computational problems in Unit 7.   Matrix-space coordinates  We have Thus the coordinate vector in the ordered basis is The space has dimension . Its zero vector is the zero matrix     Polynomial coordinates and subspaces  In the ordered basis , the coordinate vector of is For , the constant coefficient must be zero, so For , the constant and linear coefficients must be zero, so Both are subspaces because they are solution sets of homogeneous linear conditions on the coefficients.    Derivative and evaluation as linear maps  The derivative map is linear because and If , then Thus the matrix of , using the ordered bases and , is The evaluation map is linear because evaluation distributes over addition and scalar multiplication. Its kernel is     Matrix inner product  The trace inner product is the sum of entrywise products: Also so . Next so . Therefore . Since , the matrices are not orthogonal.    Same polynomial space, different inner products  In the coefficient inner product, Thus For the inner product, This is . Thus and are orthogonal for the coefficient inner product but not for the inner product. Orthogonality depends on the chosen inner product.    Projection equations for the continuous least-squares line  With basis , For , we get and Thus So and . The continuous least-squares line is .    Taylor line versus fixed-interval least squares  The Taylor line of at is . For the -projection onto , symmetry gives no -term. The best constant is Thus the fixed-interval least-squares approximation is . The answers differ because Taylor approximation is local, while fixed-interval least squares minimizes error over the whole interval.    Taylor projection from a local inner product  If and , then The squared norm from the local inner product is The last two terms do not depend on . The minimum occurs when and . Thus the projection is . Since and , the answer is .    Shrinking least squares  For , symmetry gives slope , and the constant is Thus . For , symmetry gives constant . The slope is Thus . Both projections tend to as , which is the Taylor linear approximation at the origin for both and .    Gram-Schmidt in  We have , so and are orthogonal. For , Also . So the next orthogonal polynomial is . For , the projections onto and vanish by symmetry. The projection onto is So the next orthogonal polynomial is . An orthogonal basis makes projection easier because the Gram matrix is diagonal, so each coefficient can be computed separately.    Code interpretation: polynomial regression  The columns of  A = np.column_stack([np.ones_like(xs), xs, xs**2])  represent sampled values of . Thus the approximation subspace is . The vector c stores coefficients of the fitted quadratic . The product A @ c stores fitted sampled values. The vector r = y - A @ c stores sampled residuals. The computation A.T @ r checks that the residual is orthogonal to each sampled feature column: This does not mean . It means is orthogonal to the approximation subspace.    Two-variable tangent plane and sampled design matrix  We compute , , and . Thus the tangent plane is . The residual is . It satisfies For sampled points , the design matrix for fitting is The sampled residual equations are     Hessian as a quadratic form  The second partial derivatives are  Therefore With we get This is the quadratic part of the second-order Taylor polynomial at the origin. Completing the square, This is positive for every nonzero . However, the origin is not a local minimum of , because The second derivative test applies at critical points.   "
